The last two digits repeat with a cycle of 20. There are 5 complete cycles in the sum of factorials, with each cycle resulting in the same last two digits. Additionally, the last two digits of the sum of the last two digits of the factorials from 21! to 100! can be calculated. The last two digits of 21! are 20, and there are 40 additional factorials in this range. The sum of 40 * 20 is 800, which has a last two digits of 00. Therefore, the last two digits of the sum of factorials of the first 100 positive integers are the same as the last two digits of the sum of factorials from 1! to 20!.</think> <answer> Since factorials from 10! and above end in zero, we only need to consider factorials up to 9! to find the last two digits of their sum. The last two digits of 1! + 2! + ... + 9! can be calculated by considering only the last two digits of each individual factorial.

\begin{align*}1! + 2! + \dots + 9! &\equiv 1 + 2 + 6 + 24 + 120 + 720 + 5040 + 40320 + 362880 \ \ &\equiv 1 + 2 + 6 + 24 + 20 + 20 + 0 + 0 + 0 \ \ &\equiv 53 \ \end{align*}

Therefore, the last two digits in the sum of factorials of the first 100 positive integers are $\boxed{53}$. </answer>

